title: For Sale:  Finnish M39 Mosin Nagant B Barrel on Chatellerault receiver
postcontent:
Beautiful Finn-assembled M39 "B Barrel" Mosin Nagant on an antique Chatellerault receiver. They are called B Barrels because of the "B" stamped on the barrel which is indicates that they were assembled with with barrel blanks from Belgium. The total production of B Barrel M39 is believed to be between 9-10,000 although exact figures are not known. Even though the barrels are all dated 1942, B-Barreled M39's were all assembled post war using refurbished parts. The receiver was manufactured in 1893 by Chatellerault, making this an antique rifle. B Barrels are famous for their plum colored barrel, due to the nickel-rich composition of the steel used in those Belgian barrels. I've seen much more distinct plum coloring on other B Barrels, but the color difference between the receiver and the barrel on this rifle is definitely noticeable (see pics).

Stock is in excellent condition, blueing is good and the bore is clean. Since B Barrel M39s were are assembled from refurbished parts, the numbers do not match and you will find markings from all over (ie, Tula floorplate, Chatellerault receiver w/ scrubbed Imperial Eagle).

7.62x54r

Make an offer--worst I can say is no.

title: For Sale:  Federal HST standard 50 count boxes!! 2 (LE's are 50 rounds per) boxes of LE HST 9mm 124 gr. 2 boxes LE 147 gr. and 2 LE boxes of 180 grain .40 caliber.
location: Casselberry (15-20 min. to downtown Orlando, Orlando, Florida
postcontent: I've found through lots of time spent looking for "my" round that HST's are probably the best all around defense round out there, whether 9 or .40. If you search "Dr. Robert ballistics" and go to the ar15 forum and look at the tests in bare and heavy clothed ballistic gel, they perform best in either caliber or weight of any of those tested. Perfect penetration (plus p falls a bit short of the mark), largest cavity, and widest diameter, sometimes almost double. 12 inches penetration and double diameter is about all you can ask for. Perform well through all barriers, in both 9mm weights and the 180 grain .40. Velocity really doesn't mean much except unnecessary recoil (excluding magnums and the like, but still unnecessary recoil). I switched from Gold Dot +P only to HST standard only (Ranger T 124+p is the exception to that and the plus p not worth it rule)  I had to buy 5 boxes (50 round boxes, i.e. 250 rounds) of each to get them. I already sold some .40, but have 2 left since I'm selling my .40. I am selling them for $30 each (50 round boxes). The  civilian version, which you're lucky to find even +P (expand no more than standard, more recoil, and LESS penetration because of opening earlier from velocity) sells at $30 or so for only 20 rounds. $30 for 50 is a steal. You don't have to buy all 6. I will likely give a discount if you do though (like $160 instead of $180). These are all new production in their original boxes. REDACTED.

As a result, the scope won't let you down during critical moments in the field, a must when trying to bag elusive game. The scope also includes a manual brightness adjustment override, so you can control the light output of the fiber optics to your personal preference. And to boost clarity, the scope offers a multilayer lens coating that lets in a ton of light without distorting the image.

The AccuPoint body is crafted from aircraft-quality hard-anodized aluminum to ensure a lifetime of use, with all-weather construction to protect against the tougher elements. Other advanced elements include a 30mm tube that offers a greater range of mounting options; unmatched long eye relief to protect against high-impact recoil from high-caliber rifles; easy-to-use external turret controls for windage and elevation adjustment; and a side parallax adjuster for enhanced accuracy at long range.

title: For Sale:  Very Cool Czech VZ24 Mauser Rifle with Scope
postcontent:
For your consideration, a Czech (VZ) 24 Mauser bolt action rifle chambered in 8MM Mauser, with an SVD-style side mount for an POSP scope made in Belarus (scope included). This is a very interesting rifle in that it is reminiscent of the war expedient sniper rifles used by forces during the Yugolsav Wars in the 90s. I have been unable to confirm whether or not this rifle came out of such conflict, but its features are somewhat indicative of possible militia use and not of gunsmithing in the US: The rifle serial number appears on the mount, stock and bolt, the bolt was bent to clear the scope, and there is carving (possible "trench art") on the right side of the stock depicting a howling wolf.
The side mount has clearly been professionally installed as it is rock solid and straight. The bore on the rifle is dark, but has very crisp and strong rifling. I have shot this rifle and it is very fun, accurate and reliable with surplus ammunition. The scope works perfectly (all turrets work) and the illuminated reticule works perfectly (this version has an adjustable focus as well).
I will only sell to a NH resident with a valid NH driver's license and a holder of a valid Conceal Carry Permit (no exceptions and no shipping to other states). I am only looking for cash... I am not interested in trades or vehicle services, etc., etc.

title: For Trade:  ww2 spreewerk p38
postcontent:
my ww2 spreewerk p38 for sale or trade. 

very presentable spreewerk manufactured p38 9mm pistol . "cyq" as can be seen on the left side of the frame indicates this P.38 was manufactured at Spreewerke G.m.b.H. Metallwarenfabrik, Berlin, Germany. CYQ was simply the code the Germans used for that factory so that Allies could not target specific small arm factories (similar to "ac" for Walther and "byf" for Mauser)
all matching with original magazine, serial numbers on frame, barrel, slide, & locking block match correctly' this is not a russian capture frankenstein pistol', rather being an original wartime nazi issued pistol possibly being used for post war police/military having replaced walnut grips. Minimal internal wear, shiny bore with strong grooves. decocker works fine as well as loaded chamber indicator, crisp break on the trigger, all in all a rock solid piece!
holster reads wunderlich berlin 1963. only issue being import marked very discreetly on the backstrap under the beavertail. 'very minute you wouldn't even notice' 


orvel L. Reichert who knew something about war time P-38s, produced a list that rates 1939 to 1953 P-38s from 1 to 10 based on how desirable they are. Most Spreewerk [cyq] have a letter after the serial number [ suffix }and are a 1. this p38 pistol has a letter [ a ] before the sn [ prefix] and rates a 3 as a 6th variation [a-b prefix]. The increased value of a prefix gun is also reflected on page 1434 of the 35 edition of BLUE BOOK OF GUN VALUES. The" CYQ late production second alphabet series" is about $300 more than a suffix.
